7 An Act relating to torts; creating the Good Faith
Reporting for Child Protection Act; amending 76 O.S.
8 2021, Section 31, which relates to immunity from
civil liability for volunteers, charitable
9 organizations, and not-for-profit corporations;
creating immunity for charitable organizations,
10 volunteers, and employees of charitable organizations
for disclosing sexually inappropriate conduct with a
11 minor to other charitable organizations or not-for-
profits under certain conditions; creating a
12 presumption of good faith if disclosure was made in
compliance with a reporting policy; excluding self-
13 reporting from immunity protections; defining term;
revising applicability date; providing for
14 noncodification; and providing an effective date.
15
16
17 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
18 SECTION 1. NEW LAW A new section of law not to be
19 codified in the Oklahoma Statutes reads as follows:
20 This act shall be known and may be cited as the "Good Faith
21 Reporting for Child Protection Act".
22 SECTION 2. AMENDATORY 76 O.S. 2021, Section 31, is
23 amended to read as follows:
24
ENGR. H. B. NO. 4425 Page 1

1 Section 31. A. Any volunteer shall be immune from liability in
2 a civil action on the basis of any act or omission of the volunteer
3 resulting in damage or injury if:
4 1. The volunteer was acting in good faith and within the scope
5 of the volunteer's official functions and duties for a charitable
6 organization or not-for-profit corporation; and
7 2. The damage or injury was not caused by gross negligence or
8 willful and wanton misconduct by the volunteer.
9 B. In any civil action against a charitable organization or
10 not-for-profit corporation for damages based upon the conduct of a
11 volunteer, the doctrine of respondeat superior shall apply,
12 notwithstanding the immunity granted to the volunteer in subsection
13 A of this section.
14 C. 1. Any charitable organization, volunteer, or employee of a
15 charitable organization shall be immune from liability in a civil
16 action for any act to disclose sexually inappropriate conduct with a
17 minor by the charitable organization, volunteer, or employee of a
18 charitable organization resulting in breach of contract, damages, or
19 injury if the charitable organization, volunteer, or employee of a
20 charitable organization:
21 a. was acting in good faith in the disclosure of sexually
22 inappropriate conduct with a minor to another
23 charitable organization or not-for-profit,
24
ENGR. H. B. NO. 4425 Page 2

1 b. the person who had sexually inappropriate conduct with
2 a minor was or is an employee or volunteer of the
3 disclosing charitable organization,
4 c. the disclosure was made in relation to the person's
5 current or prospective employment or volunteering with
6 the disclosed to charitable organization or not-for-
7 profit, and
8 d. reported the sexually inappropriate conduct with a
9 minor to a law enforcement agency or the Department of
10 Human Services within seventy-two (72) hours of
11 becoming aware of the sexually inappropriate conduct
12 with a minor.
13 2. A presumption of good faith shall arise if the disclosure
14 provided for in subparagraph a of paragraph 1 of this subsection was
15 made in compliance with a reporting policy adopted by the disclosing
16 charitable organization. The reporting policy shall include, but
17 not be limited to, defining actions or behaviors constituting
18 sexually inappropriate conduct with a minor.
19 3. The immunity provided for in this subsection shall not apply
20 to an individual disclosing his or her own conduct that constitutes
21 sexually inappropriate conduct with a minor.
22 D. Any person who, in good faith and without compensation, or
23 expectation of compensation, donates or loans emergency service
24 equipment to a volunteer shall not be liable for damages resulting
ENGR. H. B. NO. 4425 Page 3

1 from the use of such equipment by the volunteer, except when the
2 donor of the equipment knew or should have known that the equipment
3 was dangerous or faulty in a way which could result in bodily
4 injury, death, or damage to property.
5 D. E. Definitions.
6 1. For the purposes of this section, the term "volunteer" means
7 a person who enters into a service or undertaking of the person's
8 free will without compensation or expectation of compensation in
9 money or other thing of value in order to provide a service, care,
10 assistance, advice, or other benefit; provided, being legally
11 entitled to receive compensation for the service or undertaking
12 performed shall not preclude a person from being considered a
13 volunteer.
14 2. For the purposes of this section, the term "charitable
15 organization" means any benevolent, philanthropic, patriotic,
16 eleemosynary, educational, social, civic, recreational, religious
17 group or association, or any other person performing or purporting
18 to perform acts beneficial to the public.
19 3. For the purposes of this section, the term "not-for-profit
20 corporation" means a corporation formed for a purpose not involving
21 pecuniary gain to its shareholders or members, paying no dividends
22 or other pecuniary remuneration, directly or indirectly, to its
23 shareholders or members as such, and having no capital stock.
24
ENGR. H. B. NO. 4425 Page 4

1 4. For purposes of this section, the term "employee" means a
2 person who performs ministerial, supervisory, or staff services for
3 a charitable organization and is subject to the organization's
4 governance, direction, or authority in connection with those
5 services, regardless of tax classification. The term employee does
6 not include an independent contractor or third-party service
7 provider who retains control over the manner and means of performing
8 services.
9 E. F. The provisions of this section shall not affect the
10 liability that any person may have which arises from the operation
11 of a motor vehicle, watercraft, or aircraft in rendering the
12 service, care, assistance, advice, or other benefit as a volunteer.
13 Provided, however, the liability of any person with a current motor
14 vehicle insurance policy at the required minimum limits who
15 volunteers to provide transportation shall not exceed the limits of
16 such insurance policy, except for gross negligence or willful or
17 wanton conduct committed in providing such transportation. In no
18 event shall the limitation on liability provided under this
19 subsection apply to a person who does not possess a current motor
20 vehicle policy when providing transportation.
21 F. G. The immunity from civil liability provided for by
22 subsection A of this section shall extend only to the actions taken
23 by a person rendering the service, care, assistance, advice, or
24 other benefit as a volunteer, where such actions are agreed upon in
ENGR. H. B. NO. 4425 Page 5

1 adva nce by all involved persons to be provided on a volunteer basis.
2 This section shall not be construed to confer any immunity to any
3 person for actions taken by the volunteer prior to or after the
4 rendering of the service, care, assistance, advice, or other benefit
5 as a volunteer.
6 G. H. This section shall apply to all civil actions filed after
7 August 25, 1995 November 1, 2026.
8 SECTION 3. This act shall become effective November 1, 2026.
9 Passed the House of Representatives the 23rd day of March, 2026.
